ss.getName counts as direct reflection. It seems like it might not be an issue, but I’ll have to be careful with how I organize this. So, it's good to think this through!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test file structure**\\n\\nThe filename for Spring_bootTest seems unrelated, so I’m wondering if I should just leave it. Maybe I need to have one dedicated active class instead. Should I remove the placeholder? I could use the bash `rm` command for that. I think it’s okay to go ahead with it. However, I’m realizing that all test classes should probably be public, so I’ll remove the placeholder and create a new file with the proper package structure. Plus, I need to know about JUnit’s @TempDir dependency from the platform, and I’ll want to use AssertJ.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_k2fiZQqT0nsV5Dyj0eQX9PFD|fc_0bcd93de28d16121016a24e913e24881948080b89c2e9a2532", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.springframework.boot -path '*src/test/java*' -name '*.java' -type f | xargs -r rg \"SpringApplication|@Configuration|@SpringBootApplication|AotProcessor\" -n", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 668, "output": 1338, "cacheRead": 22528, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 24534, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780803826714, "responseId": "resp_0bcd93de28d16121016a24e8f339208194b92b2f283f32be91"}}
